LVI. ΟΝ THE BRACELET OFFERED TO HER SPOUSE BY MARIE DE LA TOUR.1

(See under preceding, No. LV.)

ARGUMENT.

Gems form one part of your bracelet, the other is a lock of hair3 both in lustre gleaming. The gems came from Venus’ shell, the same wherein she was wafted to the Cyprian shore. Their pearly whiteness is rival to the moon: smooth and round they are, like the globe itself or the milky breast of Venus. The lock of hair a nymph supplied: beside the waves of the Mense at Sedan, Love wove with these his toils for the bridegroom. ’Tis in hue like amber or gold or crocus enamelling Cilician meads. In fineness it recalls fine linen or the filaments of silk. Neither the silkworm weaving its eocoon about its own bowels‚ nor the creature that weaves with its foot its cunning workmzmship, nor the Lemnian blacksmith with all his art, is more dest and cunning. ‘Tis either a lock sent from Berenices brow, or a curl of Venus, or a tress of thy beams, O sun.
